>>34973355
That's natural. Your mind's eye will always be one of the most vital tools in your writing arsenal. Most writers will develop a vivid imagination over time, but if you were creatively engaged and often imposed your whimsy over your playtime when you were a child, then you'll have developed that organically. Children usually develop persistent paracosms by that point in their lives as well (eg the Bronte sisters), but that's a separate dissertation thesis. I had alexithymia until my late teens and spent much of my childhood exploring emotion and feeling through my characters.
>>34973720
That's precisely why it's a useful aid to writers who want to learn how to effectively outline their stories. There's a great deal of overlap between screenwriting and storywriting as distinct creative trades (or passions) under one discipline.

> mithridatism
This is actually extremely unreliable due to multiple reasons. First and foremost is the fact that only certain biological compounds can have an immunity built for them, in part due to the various ways that these poisons are filtered by the body.
Second, the way the body builds this immunity is by conditioning your liver to create more enzymes that metabolism the poison or venom in question, which has its own set of issues. The bad stuff gets metabolized into other stuff, which can build up. This less bad stuff is still bad. This can lead to liver damage or other liver issues.

Finally, some poisons/venoms just straight up bypass the immune system of the body, meaning the bad stuff in question doesn’t even get the chance to be filtered before you die.

Also, neurotoxin, even if filtered, still causes permanent nerve damage. Anything that causes nerve damage will still cause it even with immunity, as the stuff needs to metabolize and in the time that takes some damage can still be done.

Realistically you would just keep anti venom on you at all times.
